```text
Layer 1 Pseudocode — Raw Marker QC for OptiTrack / Motive Data

Goal:
  Evaluate the quality of the raw optical marker measurements before trusting
  Motive-solved skeleton kinematics in Layer 2 and JcvPCA analysis in Layer 3.

Core principle:
  Layer 1 detects, flags, summarizes, and reports raw marker artifacts.
  Layer 1 does not repair marker data.
  Layer 1 does not compute final joint angles.
  Layer 1 does not create JcvPCA features.

Input:
  raw_marker_csv:
    CSV containing raw marker XYZ trajectories from Motive.

Optional input:
  segment_boundaries.csv:
    Manually/video-verified Layer 3 analysis windows.
    Example:
      T1_P1_r1_Group4
      T1_P1_r2_Group4
      T2_P1_r1_Group4
      ...

Output:
  raw_marker_qc_report.csv
  raw_marker_missingness_by_marker.csv
  raw_marker_jump_flags.csv
  raw_marker_velocity_spike_flags.csv
  raw_marker_segment_length_report.csv
  raw_marker_unlabeled_marker_report.csv
  raw_marker_window_qc_summary.csv
  raw_marker_qc_metadata.json

================================================================================
PART 0 — IMPORTANT ASSUMPTIONS
================================================================================

Layer 1 uses raw marker trajectories only.

Layer 1 supports the question:
  "Was the optical measurement stable during the analysis windows used later?"

Layer 1 does not prove anatomical correctness.

Layer 1 does not replace Layer 2.

Layer 1 outputs should be used as QC evidence when interpreting Layer 3.

Important limitation:
  A clean raw-marker QC report supports trust in the measurement window,
  but it does not prove that Motive’s solved skeleton is anatomically perfect.

================================================================================
PART 1 — LOAD RAW MARKER CSV
================================================================================

Function load_raw_marker_csv(file_path):

  Read CSV.

  Detect frame column:
    Possible names:
      Frame
      frame
      FrameNumber

  Detect time column:
    Possible names:
      Time
      time
      Timestamp
      Seconds

  Detect marker position columns.

  Expected marker format examples:
    MarkerName:X
    MarkerName:Y
    MarkerName:Z

    or:
    MarkerName_Position_X
    MarkerName_Position_Y
    MarkerName_Position_Z

  For each detected marker:
    Confirm that X, Y, Z columns exist.

  Separate:
    labeled_markers
    unlabeled_marker_columns, if present

  Output:
    raw_marker_dataframe
    marker_inventory

  Export:
    raw_marker_inventory.csv

marker_inventory.csv columns:
  marker_name
  x_column
  y_column
  z_column
  marker_type
  has_x
  has_y
  has_z
  n_frames
  n_missing_x
  n_missing_y
  n_missing_z

Hard stop if:
  no frame column is found
  no time column is found
  no marker XYZ triplets are found

Warning if:
  some markers are missing one coordinate component
  marker naming is ambiguous
  unlabeled marker columns are present but cannot be parsed cleanly

Weak point:
  Motive CSV exports can vary in naming structure.
  Marker parsing must be explicit and should not silently guess incorrectly.

================================================================================
PART 2 — VALIDATE FRAME AND TIME BASE
================================================================================

Function validate_frame_time(raw_marker_dataframe):

  Check:
    frame is monotonic increasing
    no duplicated frames
    no missing frame IDs if frame IDs are integer-continuous
    time is monotonic increasing
    no duplicated timestamps
    no negative time differences

  Compute:
    dt = time[t] - time[t-1]
    median_dt
    min_dt
    max_dt
    estimated_sampling_rate_hz = 1 / median_dt

  Expected:
    approximately 120 Hz

  Flag:
    duplicated frames
    missing frame IDs
    large time gaps
    nonmonotonic time steps
    unexpected sampling rate

  Export:
    raw_marker_frame_time_validation_report.csv

Hard stop if:
    time is nonmonotonic
    many duplicated frames exist
    sampling rate cannot be estimated

Warning if:
    isolated dropped frames exist
    estimated sampling rate differs from expected value

Weak point:
  Marker velocity and jump checks depend on correct frame/time spacing.
  If time is wrong, artifact scores may be misleading.

================================================================================
PART 3 — BUILD MARKER POSITION TABLE
================================================================================

Function build_marker_position_table(raw_marker_dataframe, marker_inventory):

  For each labeled marker:
    Extract:
      marker_x
      marker_y
      marker_z

  Convert empty strings and invalid numeric values to NaN.

  Preserve:
    frame
    time

  Output:
    marker_position_table

  Export:
    raw_marker_positions.parquet

Check:
    all marker coordinates are numeric
    NaN values are preserved, not silently filled
    units are documented, e.g. meters or millimeters

Metadata:
    marker_position_units

Weak point:
  Motive exports may use millimeters or meters depending on settings.
  Velocity thresholds depend strongly on units.

================================================================================
PART 4 — MISSINGNESS CHECK
================================================================================

Function compute_marker_missingness(marker_position_table):

  For each marker:

    A frame is missing if:
      X is NaN OR Y is NaN OR Z is NaN

    Compute:
      n_frames_total
      n_missing_frames
      missing_percent
      max_consecutive_missing_frames
      first_missing_frame
      last_missing_frame

  Export:
    raw_marker_missingness_by_marker.csv

raw_marker_missingness_by_marker.csv columns:
  marker_name
  n_frames_total
  n_missing_frames
  missing_percent
  max_consecutive_missing_frames
  first_missing_frame
  last_missing_frame

Recommended flags:
  missing_percent_high
  max_gap_high

Example thresholds:
  missing_percent_high if missing_percent > 5%
  max_gap_high if max_consecutive_missing_frames > 10 frames

Thresholds must be configurable.

Weak point:
  Missing raw marker data can exist even if Layer 2 solved skeleton quaternions
  contain no missing values.

================================================================================
PART 5 — MARKER JUMP CHECK
================================================================================

Function detect_marker_jumps(marker_position_table, sampling_rate_hz):

  For each marker:

    For each frame t > 0:

      p_t:
        [x[t], y[t], z[t]]

      p_prev:
        [x[t-1], y[t-1], z[t-1]]

      If either p_t or p_prev contains NaN:
        jump[t] = NaN
        skip flagging for this frame

      Else:
        displacement[t] = norm(p_t - p_prev)

    Compute robust threshold:
      median_displacement = median(displacement ignoring NaN)
      mad_displacement = median_absolute_deviation(displacement ignoring NaN)

      jump_threshold = median_displacement + K_jump * mad_displacement

    Default:
      K_jump = 8
      configurable

    Flag:
      jump_flag[t] = displacement[t] > jump_threshold

  Export:
    raw_marker_jump_flags.csv
    raw_marker_jump_summary.csv

raw_marker_jump_flags.csv columns:
  frame
  time
  marker_name
  displacement
  jump_threshold
  jump_flag

raw_marker_jump_summary.csv columns:
  marker_name
  n_jump_flags
  jump_flags_per_minute
  max_frame_to_frame_displacement
  median_frame_to_frame_displacement
  jump_threshold

Weak point:
  Gaga movement can be fast and expressive.
  Fixed thresholds may falsely flag real movement.
  Prefer robust marker-specific thresholds first, then inspect large flags.

================================================================================
PART 6 — MARKER VELOCITY SPIKE CHECK
================================================================================

Function detect_velocity_spikes(marker_position_table, sampling_rate_hz):

  For each marker:

    For each frame t > 0:

      If position[t] or position[t-1] contains NaN:
        velocity[t] = NaN

      Else:
        dt = time[t] - time[t-1]
        velocity[t] = norm(position[t] - position[t-1]) / dt

    Compute robust threshold:
      median_velocity = median(velocity ignoring NaN)
      mad_velocity = median_absolute_deviation(velocity ignoring NaN)

      velocity_threshold = median_velocity + K_velocity * mad_velocity

    Default:
      K_velocity = 8
      configurable

    Flag:
      velocity_spike_flag[t] = velocity[t] > velocity_threshold

  Export:
    raw_marker_velocity_spike_flags.csv
    raw_marker_velocity_summary.csv

raw_marker_velocity_spike_flags.csv columns:
  frame
  time
  marker_name
  velocity
  velocity_threshold
  velocity_spike_flag

raw_marker_velocity_summary.csv columns:
  marker_name
  max_velocity
  median_velocity
  velocity_threshold
  n_velocity_spike_flags
  velocity_spike_flags_per_minute

Weak point:
  Velocity spikes and marker jumps are related but not identical.
  Both are useful because a velocity spike can reveal artifact-like behavior even
  when displacement thresholds are borderline.

================================================================================
PART 7 — UNLABELED MARKER BURST CHECK
================================================================================

Function detect_unlabeled_marker_bursts(raw_marker_dataframe):

  If no unlabeled marker columns are present:
    Export report stating:
      "No unlabeled marker columns detected."
    Return.

  For each frame:

    Count number of visible unlabeled markers:
      n_unlabeled_visible[frame]

    A marker is visible if:
      at least one of X/Y/Z is non-NaN
      or all three X/Y/Z are valid, depending on export format.

  Compute:
    median_unlabeled_visible
    mad_unlabeled_visible
    burst_threshold = median + K_unlabeled * MAD

  Default:
    K_unlabeled = 6
    configurable

  Flag:
    unlabeled_burst_flag[frame] =
      n_unlabeled_visible[frame] > burst_threshold

  Export:
    raw_marker_unlabeled_marker_report.csv
    raw_marker_unlabeled_burst_flags.csv

raw_marker_unlabeled_marker_report.csv columns:
  frame
  time
  n_unlabeled_visible
  burst_threshold
  unlabeled_burst_flag

Weak point:
  Unlabeled marker bursts are indirect evidence.
  They do not automatically invalidate the trial, but they may indicate tracking instability.

================================================================================
PART 8 — SEGMENT-LENGTH PLAUSIBILITY CHECK
================================================================================

Function load_marker_pair_map(marker_pair_map_path):

  Load marker pairs expected to remain approximately stable.

Expected columns:
  pair_name
  marker_a
  marker_b
  body_region
  include_in_qc

Example:
  left_upper_arm_pair, LUpperArm1, LUpperArm2, left_arm, true
  pelvis_pair, LPelvis, RPelvis, pelvis, true
  trunk_pair, Sternum, Spine, trunk, true

Validate:
  marker_a exists
  marker_b exists
  pair_name is unique
  include_in_qc is true/false

Export:
  marker_pair_map_used.csv


Function compute_segment_length_plausibility(marker_position_table, marker_pair_map):

  For each marker pair:

    For each frame:

      If marker_a or marker_b contains NaN:
        distance[frame] = NaN

      Else:
        distance[frame] = norm(position_a - position_b)

    Compute:
      median_distance
      std_distance
      coefficient_of_variation = std_distance / median_distance
      max_deviation_from_median
      max_deviation_percent

    Compute robust threshold:
      distance_deviation = abs(distance - median_distance)
      threshold = median(distance_deviation) + K_segment * MAD(distance_deviation)

    Default:
      K_segment = 8
      configurable

    Flag:
      segment_length_flag[frame] =
        distance_deviation[frame] > threshold

  Export:
    raw_marker_segment_length_report.csv
    raw_marker_segment_length_flags.csv

raw_marker_segment_length_report.csv columns:
  pair_name
  marker_a
  marker_b
  body_region
  median_distance
  std_distance
  coefficient_of_variation
  max_deviation_percent
  n_segment_length_flags

Weak point:
  Segment-length plausibility is not proof of anatomical accuracy.
  It only checks whether selected marker distances are stable enough to support tracking consistency.

================================================================================
PART 9 — CREATE FRAME-LEVEL ARTIFACT TABLE
================================================================================

Function create_frame_level_artifact_table():

  For each frame:

    Count:
      n_missing_markers
      n_marker_jump_flags
      n_velocity_spike_flags
      n_unlabeled_burst_flags
      n_segment_length_flags

    Compute:
      any_marker_artifact =
        n_missing_markers > 0 OR
        n_marker_jump_flags > 0 OR
        n_velocity_spike_flags > 0 OR
        n_unlabeled_burst_flags > 0 OR
        n_segment_length_flags > 0

    Optional weighted artifact score:
      frame_artifact_score =
        w_missing * n_missing_markers +
        w_jump * n_marker_jump_flags +
        w_velocity * n_velocity_spike_flags +
        w_unlabeled * n_unlabeled_burst_flags +
        w_segment * n_segment_length_flags

  Export:
    raw_marker_frame_artifact_table.csv

raw_marker_frame_artifact_table.csv columns:
  frame
  time
  n_missing_markers
  n_marker_jump_flags
  n_velocity_spike_flags
  n_unlabeled_burst_flags
  n_segment_length_flags
  any_marker_artifact
  frame_artifact_score

Weak point:
  The artifact score is a QC summary, not a validated biological measure.
  Use it to guide inspection, not as the only decision rule.

================================================================================
PART 10 — SEGMENT-LEVEL QC SUMMARY
================================================================================

Function compute_segment_qc_summary(segment_boundaries, frame_artifact_table):

  Input:
    segment_boundaries.csv

Expected segment_boundaries columns:
  subject_id
  timepoint
  part_id
  repetition_id
  group_id
  task_id optional
  start_time
  end_time
  boundary_source
  boundary_verified_true_false

  For each segment:

    Select frames where:
      start_time <= time <= end_time

    Compute:
      n_frames
      duration_sec
      mean_missing_markers
      max_missing_markers
      n_frames_with_missing_markers
      percent_frames_with_missing_markers
      n_jump_flags
      n_velocity_spike_flags
      n_unlabeled_burst_frames
      n_segment_length_flags
      n_any_artifact_frames
      percent_any_artifact_frames
      mean_frame_artifact_score
      max_frame_artifact_score

    Assign qc_status:
      pass
      warning
      fail

  Suggested qc_status rule:
    fail if:
      percent_any_artifact_frames > fail_percent_threshold
      OR severe marker gaps overlap the segment
      OR repeated large jumps occur in key markers

    warning if:
      artifact burden is nonzero but below fail threshold

    pass if:
      artifact burden is low

  Thresholds must be configurable.

  Export:
    raw_marker_window_qc_summary.csv

raw_marker_window_qc_summary.csv columns:
  subject_id
  timepoint
  part_id
  repetition_id
  group_id
  task_id
  start_time
  end_time
  duration_sec
  n_frames
  percent_frames_with_missing_markers
  n_jump_flags
  n_velocity_spike_flags
  n_unlabeled_burst_frames
  n_segment_length_flags
  percent_any_artifact_frames
  mean_frame_artifact_score
  max_frame_artifact_score
  qc_status
  qc_notes

Important:
  Segment boundaries are defined by task/video logic.
  QC evaluates the chosen segment.
  QC should not be used to secretly choose the cleanest segment.

Weak point:
  Because segmentation happens before Layer 3, this segment-level QC can be
  computed after boundaries are verified and before JcvPCA interpretation.

