================================================================================
PART 14 — IMPLEMENTATION WEAK POINTS TO HANDLE CAREFULLY
================================================================================

1. CSV parsing:
   Motive raw marker exports may have inconsistent column naming.
   Parser should be explicit and should fail loudly when ambiguous.

2. Marker units:
   Confirm whether positions are in meters or millimeters.
   Velocity and displacement thresholds depend on this.

3. Missing values:
   Do not silently interpolate or fill missing marker values in Layer 1.
   Preserve missingness and report it.

4. Thresholds:
   Gaga movement is unconstrained and can be fast.
   Prefer robust marker-specific thresholds over rigid universal thresholds.

5. Unlabeled markers:
   Treat unlabeled marker bursts as warning evidence, not automatic failure.

6. Segment-length pairs:
   Marker-pair map must be reviewed manually.
   Bad marker pairs create misleading segment-length flags.

7. Segment QC:
   Segment boundaries must come from task/video logic.
   QC evaluates those windows; it should not define them.

8. Layer separation:
   Layer 1 QC does not create Layer 3 features.
   Final kinematic variables come from Layer 2.

9. Interpretation:
   A clean Layer 1 report supports measurement stability.
   It does not prove anatomical validity of Motive-solved skeleton kinematics.

10. Reporting:
   Always report QC status per full recording and per Layer 3 analysis segment.
